es the rise and fall of the new math as a marker of the period’s political and social ferment. Neither the new math curriculum designers nor its diverse legions of supporters concentrated on whether the new math would improve students’ calculation ability. Rather, they felt the new math would train children to think in the right way, instilling in students a set of mental habits that might better prepare them to be citizens of modern society—a world of complex challenges, rapid technological change, and unforeseeable futures. While Phillips grounds his argument in shifting perceptions of intellectual discipline and the underlying nature of mathematical knowledge, he also touches on long-standing debates over the place and relevance of mathematics in liberal education. And in so doing, he explores the essence of what it means to be an intelligent American—by the numbers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEducation and statezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMathematicsxStudy and teachingxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aMathematicsxStudy and teachingzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  apolitics, mathematics, political, history, historical, era, time period, academic, scholarly, research, america, american, united states, usa, postwar, wartime, beatnik, hippies, feminism, video game, schools, schooling, 1950s, 1960s, cold war, intellectual, exceptionalism, nationalism, technology, technological, sputnik, knowledge, global, international, curriculum, pedagogy, modern, contemporary, arithmetic.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022618496840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226185019423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226185019/original  